@endnode

@node "Insta" "How to do ...."

This is easy! First start the INSTALL script to clone your ENV-Archive
directory. Then load your startup-sequence with an editor and edit this
one like following (I recommend you to make a backup of your original
startup-sequence!!!):

First search for the line ...

   C:Copy >NIL: ENVARC: RAM:ENV ALL NOREQ

and remove this one. Then you`ve to search the line ...

   Assign >NIL: ENV: RAM:ENV

and change this one to ...

   Assign >NIL: ENV: SYS:Prefs/Env

and that`s all. Then simply reboot your mashine and you`ll have got a
nice amount of more memory. Now you can also put as much things into
this directory (like lotsa def-icons) as you want without loosing any
memory. Read @{"Troubleshooting" link "Troub" 0} for problems and hints!!!

  @{"Back to the menu!" link "MAIN" 0} 

@endnode

@node "Troub" "Troubleshooting ... as always!!!"

Please remember that the ENV directory is now on your HD and can`t be
removed with rebooting your mashine. If you change anything on your con-
figuration and you click on the USE button, this configuration will also
appear after rebooting.

So simply start your Prefs-tool or whatever again and select the option
"Last saved". Another way is simply to clean your ENV directory and to
copy all files from ENV-Archive to ENV.

Anyway, you can also use the script called "CleanUp", this will do all
these things for you automatically! You can also include this script
into your startup-sequence, then you won`t have got this problem. Then
simply just add anywhere in your startup-sequence following lines ...

          C:delete SYS:Prefs/env/* all quiet force
          C:copy SYS:Prefs/Env-archive SYS:Prefs/ENV all quiet

But remember that your mashine will boot a bit slower then. And you`ve
to include these lines BEFORE any tool is started which needs the ENV
directory (ofcourse)!

  @{"Back to the menu!" link "MAIN" 0} 

@endnode

